### ----- sshd_config_hardened -----

# Change default port (optional, reduces noise from bots)
Port 2222
# Disable password login
PasswordAuthentication no
# Disable direct root login
PermitRootLogin no
# Allow public key auth
PubkeyAuthentication yes
# Limit authentication attempts
MaxAuthTries 3
# Recommended: disable extra auth mechanisms (optional)
ChallengeResponseAuthentication no
KerberosAuthentication no
GSSAPIAuthentication no
# Disable forwarding features (optional but safer)
AllowTcpForwarding no
AllowAgentForwarding no
X11Forwarding no
# Use stronger crypto (optional; adjust if your SSH version complains)
KexAlgorithms curve25519-sha256,curve25519-sha256@libssh.org
Ciphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com
MACs hmac-sha2-512,hmac-sha2-256
# Session / liveness controls (optional)
ClientAliveInterval 300
ClientAliveCountMax 2
LoginGraceTime 30
# More logging for security monitoring
LogLevel VERBOSE

# ----- Save as /etc/ssh/sshd_config -----

```bash
sudo sshd -t && sudo systemctl reload sshd
```

### Why disable PasswordAuthentication?

Because it makes brute-force/password-guessing attacks much easier. If SSH passwords are enabled:

attackers can repeatedly try passwords (often at scale),
any weak password (or reused password) becomes a direct path to access. With password auth disabled, users must authenticate using SSH keys, which are generally more secure (and harder to guess).

### Why disable PermitRootLogin?

To prevent direct login as the root user over SSH. Even if an attacker gains some access, denying root login reduces impact. Typically:

a normal user logs in,
then access is elevated only via controlled mechanisms like sudo (with audit logs and policies), instead of giving full system control immediately.

### How to monitor failed login attempts?

Using your example log check:

```bash
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log
```

### Live monitoring:

```bash
sudo tail -f /var/log/auth.log | grep --line-buffered "Failed password"
```